thers chose to follow their advice. Her analysis considers the medical discourse of the time, the development of free services made available to mothers between 1910 and 1970, and how mothers used these services. Showing the variety of social actors involved in this process (doctors, nurses, women’s groups, members of the clergy, private enterprise, the state, and the mothers themselves), this study delineates the alliances and the conflicts that arose between them in a complex phenomenon that profoundly changed the nature of childbearing in Quebec. Un Québec en mal d’enfants: La médicalisation de la maternité 1910—1970 was awarded the Clio-Québec Prize, the Lionel Groulx-Yves-Saint-Germain Prize, and the Jean-Charles-Falardeau Prize. This translation by W. Donald Wilson brings this important book to a new readership.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChild carexHistoryx20th centuryxQuébec (Province). 0aChild carezQuébec (Province)xHistoryy20th century. 0aChild carezQuébec (Province)xHistoryy20th century. 0aContrôle socialxHistoirex20e sièclexQuébec (Province). 0aMaternal health servicesxHistoryx20th centuryxQuébec (Province). 0aMaternal health serviceszQuébec (Province)xHistoryy20th century. 0aMaternal health serviceszQuébec (Province)xHistoryy20th century. 0aMèresxSoins médicauxxHistoirex20e sièclexQuébec (Province). 0aNewborn infantsxCarexHistoryx20th centuryxQuébec (Province). 0aNewborn infantsxCarezQuébec (Province)xHistoryy20th century. 0aNewborn infantsxCarezQuébec (Province)xHistoryy20th century. 0aNewborn infantsxMortalityxHistoryx20th centuryxQuébec (Province). 0aNewborn infantsxMortalityzQuébec (Province)xHistoryy20th century. 0aNewborn infantsxMortalityzQuébec (Province)xHistoryy20th century. 0aNouveau-nésxMortalitéxHistoirex20